					"contents": "Applied advanced electronic structure methods to investigate bonding, reactivity, and non-covalent interactions, while developing and deploying predictive computational workflows for multidisciplinary research in fundamental chemistry, catalysis, and materials science. Oversaw large-scale data pipelines and ensured rigorous data governance, meeting all institutional requirements. Translated complex computational insights into actionable strategies, streamlined scientific processes, and contributed to evolving data management practices.\n\nApplied advanced electronic structure methods to investigate bonding, reactivity, and non-covalent interactions, while developing and deploying predictive computational workflows for multidisciplinary research in fundamental chemistry, catalysis, and materials science.\n\nManage and analyze large-scale computational datasets to model chemical systems, identify trends, and improve predictive accuracy. Develop and optimize automated workflows for high-performance computing, enhancing efficiency and reproducibility. Ensure data integrity and structured reporting by translating complex findings into actionable insights for interdisciplinary teams. Collaborate with researchers across disciplines to refine methodologies, assess uncertainties, and drive data-driven decision-making.\n\nDear Hiring Team,\n\nI am excited to apply for the City Research Scientist (Level II) position with the NYPD. With a PhD in computational chemistry and a background in data analysis, program evaluation, and structured reporting, I specialize in analyzing complex datasets, developing automated workflows, and translating technical findings into actionable insights. My experience managing high-performance computing workflows, ensuring data integrity, and collaborating across disciplines aligns well with the analytical and problem-solving aspects of this role.\n\nI look forward to the opportunity to contribute my expertise to your team. Please feel free to reach out if you require any additional information.\n\nBest regards,\nAndrew Molino\n\n\n\nApplied advanced quantitative analysis and computational modeling to identify patterns, optimize predictive methodologies, and support data-driven decision-making in complex research environments. Developed and automated analytical workflows, managing large-scale data pipelines to ensure accuracy, efficiency, and compliance with institutional standards. Synthesized complex datasets into actionable insights, streamlining research processes and contributing to improved data governance and strategic analysis.\n\n\nTheoretical Chemistry,Computational Chemistry,Predictive Analysis,Molecular Design,Density Functional Theory,Version control,Laboratory Operations,Data Handling,Data Management,Python,Bash,Strategic Planning,Molecular Modeling,Data Workflows,Academic Research,Data-Driven Insights,Collaboration,Data Analysis,Anaconda,Matlab,Matplotlib,Workflow Automation,Job Scheduling,High-Performance Computing,PBS,Slurm,Github,Quantum Chemistry, Numpy,Pandas,Linux,Predictive Modeling,Materials Science,Energy Decomposition Analysis,Non-Covalent Interactions,Electrostatic Interactions,Molecular Interactions,Optimization,Electronic Spectroscopy,Electron Paramagnetic Resonance\n\nDuring a previous project, a graduate student was discovered fabricating data for a research assignment. The institutional academic integrity policy expressly prohibited data manipulation, which prompted an immediate review. A focused meeting was arranged to explain the policy’s stipulations and its potential consequences, including disciplinary measures. The presentation of evidence was clear and factual, highlighting how such violations undermine both scientific credibility and institutional standards. The student acknowledged the infraction, re-collected the data under supervised conditions, and complied with all guidelines moving forward, which reinforced the culture of honesty in the research environment.\n\nThis role aligns with personal and professional goals by providing a setting that upholds rigorous ethical standards, promotes data integrity, and advances high-quality research outcomes. It allows for an active contribution to a transparent and accountable scientific community, ensuring that all investigations and discoveries rest on reliable, verifiable foundations.\n\nOne data visualization I find particularly compelling is the interactive electoral map on https://www.270towin.com. As someone with a strong interest in history, I appreciate how it allows users to explore historical election outcomes while also experimenting with real-time projections and what-if scenarios. The ability to toggle between past and present elections provides valuable insights into political trends and voter behavior over time.\n\nWhat makes this visualization stand out is its interactivity, which transforms historical data into a fun and engaging learning experience. Rather than passively viewing results, users can manipulate scenarios and see instant feedback, fueling curiosity and deeper exploration.\n\nThis visualization highlights how interactive tools make complex data more intuitive and engaging, a principle that applies to scientific data visualization as well. Well-designed visualizations not only communicate insights but also encourage discovery, an approach that is invaluable in analyzing biological and chemical data.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nRecently, I worked on a project investigating the electronic structure and steric effects on boron-doped heterocycles. The goal was to determine how altering ligand sterics influenced biradical character and photophysical properties, with potential applications in materials science.\n\nUsing density functional theory (DFT) and multireference CASSCF methods, I developed computational workflows to automate and analyze electronic structures, quantify biradical character, and predict spectroscopic signatures. A key question was: How do steric effects influence the balance between open-shell biradical and closed-shell electronic configurations? By sampling the potential energy surface (PES) through conformational analysis, I explored a wide range of structures from which I could extract key electronic and geometric trends. This approach allowed me to identify stabilizing π-interactions and steric repulsion effects, refining our understanding of structure-property relationships in these systems.\n\nBeyond theoretical insights, this project required automating large-scale calculations, handling high-performance computing environments, and visualizing complex datasets to interpret electronic distributions and excited-state behavior effectively. The findings guided experimental synthesis efforts, validating predictions and informing future molecular designs.\n\nThis project reinforced the power of computational modeling in predicting molecular behavior and highlighted the importance of clear data visualization in translating complex quantum chemical insights into actionable experimental strategies.\n\n\n\nWhat kind of opportunities are you looking for? Describe your area of interest (type of position for which you are looking) or degree focus area(s).*\n \tI am seeking opportunities in computational modeling, process development, and materials optimization, where I can leverage my expertise in quantum chemistry, high-throughput screening, and predictive modeling to improve material properties and manufacturing efficiency. I am particularly interested in roles that involve computational workflow automation, high-performance computing for process optimization, and data-driven approaches to materials design. My background in electronic structure modeling, materials screening, and automation positions me well for roles in semiconductor manufacturing, materials science, and process engineering, where I can contribute to innovation and efficiency improvements.\n\nProvide your salary/hourly range expectation.*\n\tI am open to discussing compensation based on the role's responsibilities and Intel's pay structure. Based on my research and level of expertise, I expect a salary in the range of $110,000 - $140,000 per year, depending on the total compensation package, benefits, and opportunities for career growth.\n\n\nM&S Skills\n\nQuantitative Analysis, Predictive Modeling, Data-Driven Insights, Statistical Analysis, Forecasting, Decision Optimization, Python, NumPy, Pandas, Matplotlib, Bash, MATLAB, Data Workflows, High-Performance Computing, Workflow Automation, Version Control (GitHub), Linux, Job Scheduling (PBS, SLURM), Data Handling, Data Management, Strategic Research, Computational Methods, Research Optimization, Data Interpretation, Algorithm Development, Trend Identification, Large-Scale Data Processing, Collaboration, Communication, Interdisciplinary Research, Technical Presentation, Analytical Problem-Solving.\n\nDuring my PhD and postdoctoral research in theoretical chemistry, I developed a strong analytical mindset, routinely identifying patterns, automating data workflows, and synthesising complex findings into actionable insights. This experience equipped me to process large datasets efficiently, recognise anomalies, and produce structured reports—key skills that directly align with signals intelligence requirements.\n\nIn my work, I have created optimised computational workflows and data pipelines that not only reduced processing time but also improved accuracy, demonstrating a capacity for intelligence processing and analysis. Beyond technical expertise, I thrive in collaborative, high-pressure environments. Working on international research teams has challenged me to communicate complex results clearly, support operational decision-making, and mentor colleagues in data interpretation and structured reporting.\n\nAlthough I have not previously dealt with classified intelligence, I fully appreciate the importance of data integrity, security-conscious decision-making, and structured methodologies. I am eager to leverage my analytical background, problem-solving abilities, and collaborative mindset in support of ASD’s mission in signals intelligence and operational analysis.\n\nI am currently working at MIT in Boston, USA, under a contract position until May 15, 2025. However, I am fully available at any stage of the recruitment process to further discuss my application.",
