					"contents": "To disentangle the effects of the phenyl substituents from the intrinsic electronic properties of the ladder silicon framework, we performed TD-DFT calculations on model compounds representing the monocyclic (11), bicyclic (trans-3), and tricyclic (tst-9) systems, each bearing methyl (Me), trimethylsilyl (TMS), or phenyl (Ph) substituents. The calculations, carried out at [Insert Level of Theory/Basis Set], provided energies (in nm) and oscillator strengths for the first five singlet excited states (S₁–S₅), as summarized in Table [X]. These data offer quantitative insight into the transitions that govern the experimental absorption onset (λ_onset).\n\nIn the phenyl-substituted series (11-Ph, trans-3-Ph, tst-9-Ph), the calculated spectra are dominated by transitions that involve the π-system of the phenyl rings. For instance, in tst-9-Ph the lowest excited state (S₁) is predicted at 316 nm, but with a negligible oscillator strength (f = 1.2 × 10⁻⁷), indicative of a symmetry-forbidden σ(Si–Si) → π*(Ph) transition. Instead, transitions such as the S₂ state at 308.7 nm (f = 0.3047) and the S₅ state at 299.9 nm (f = 0.1210) are more intense, suggesting that they are dominated by π→π* character or involve mixed transitions. Similar trends in 11-Ph and trans-3-Ph confirm that the phenyl groups substantially complicate the interpretation of the silicon framework’s intrinsic σ→σ* transitions, as the low-energy forbidden state is effectively obscured by subsequent bright transitions.\n\nIn contrast, the methyl-substituted compounds reveal a clearer picture of the inherent electronic properties of the silicon framework. In the monocyclic 11-Me system, the first excited state with appreciable oscillator strength appears as the S₃/S₄ transitions at 235.9 nm and 235.7 nm (f ≈ 0.05). For the bicyclic trans-3-Me, the dominant bright transition shifts to 281.2 nm (S₁, f = 0.0748), and in the tricyclic tst-9-Me, the S₁ transition further red-shifts to 302.9 nm (f = 0.2918). This systematic red shift, coupled with increasing oscillator strengths, supports the hypothesis that elongating the all-trans silicon chain decreases the HOMO–LUMO gap and enhances electronic delocalization.\n\nThe TMS-substituted compounds exhibit similar trends, albeit with some nuances. In 11-TMS, the S₁ transition is calculated at 259.4 nm (f = 0.098), while in trans-3-TMS the first bright transitions occur at 278.5 nm (f = 0.0528) and 275.8 nm (f = 0.1148). For tst-9-TMS, the S₁ transition is predicted at 293.9 nm with a robust oscillator strength of 0.3847. Although the red shift with increasing ring number is maintained, the TMS series consistently shows slightly shorter wavelengths compared to the methyl series. This observation suggests that the TMS groups, likely through inductive and hyperconjugative effects, subtly influence the electronic structure and modulate the degree of σ-conjugation in the silicon framework.\n\nOverall, these TD-DFT results quantitatively confirm that increasing the number of fused rings in ladder cyclosilanes produces a measurable red shift in the lowest-energy transition with appreciable oscillator strength. For the methyl- and TMS-substituted series, λ_onset shifts from approximately 236 nm in the monocyclic framework to 281 nm in the bicyclic, and to 303 nm (or 294 nm for TMS) in the tricyclic systems. In phenyl-substituted systems, the lowest-energy transition is symmetry-forbidden, and the experimentally observed λ_onset corresponds to the first bright transition, which is influenced by the phenyl π-system. These findings not only validate the role of σ-conjugation in determining the electronic properties of ladder cyclosilanes but also emphasize how exocyclic substituents can modulate these properties. The insights gleaned from this computational study provide a solid foundation for guiding future synthetic strategies aimed at optimizing the optical characteristics of silicon-based materials.",
